entry.title: Update two unit tests to work with Citadel checks.
entry.content:
This fixes two problems in unit tests that are blocking the

re-enabling of Citadel protections in ChildProcessSecurityPolicy.

Citadel checks enforce that an unlocked/non-isolated process can't

commit or access data belonging to a site that requires a dedicated

process locked to that site. See crbug.com/764958 for more details.



1. Two tests, AdTagCarriesAcrossProcesses and

PrepareDropDataForChildProcess_LocalFiles, instantiate a default

BrowserTaskEnvironment, which causes trouble for thread-sensitive

security checks performed in ChildProcessSecurityPolicy. In

particular, CPSP gets confused because

BrowserThread::CurrentlyOn(BrowserThread::IO) and

BrowserThread::CurrentlyOn(BrowserThread::UI) both return true, so it

can't properly enforce that it's running on the UI thread. (Our goal

is to restrict CPSP to UI thread only, since not all security checks

can be performed on the IO thread.)



To fix this, pass REAL_IO_THREAD when instantiating

BrowserTaskEnvironment.



2. AdTagCarriesAcrossProcesses uses IsolateAllSitesForTesting() in its

test body to force strict site isolation, but that is too late to

apply to a navigation that its test class performs in SetUp(). As a

result, when running on Android where there's no site isolation, that

initial navigation in SetUp() runs without strict site isolation and

subsequent navigations run with strict site isolation, causing citadel

security checks in CPSP to later fail, because it think that something

that now requires a dedicated process was allowed into an unlocked

process. Strict site isolation mode cannot be changed dynamically, so

it must be set prior to any navigations. This CL ensures that this is

the case by moving IsolateAllSitesForTesting() to be done in the test

constructor.



See also

https://chromium-review.googlesource.com/c/chromium/src/+/4764617 for

more context, which provided the basis for the first part of the fix

in this CL.

entry.title: Move request_file_set_ checks from CanCommitURL to CanRequestURL
entry.content:
ChildProcessSecurityPolicy (CPSP) maintains a set of files that a

renderer process is permitted to request in a request_file_set_ map

stored in SecurityState. This was originally introduced in 2012 in

https://chromiumcodereview-private.appspot.com/10517009 to fix

https://crbug.com/127525, where dragging a file onto a frame exposed

access to the entire file: scheme (i.e., all local files), rather than

the specific dragged file. At that time, request_file_set_

enforcement was done when CPSP::CanRequestURL() checked

SecurityState::CanRequestURL(). There was no CPSP::CanCommitURL() or

SecurityState::CanCommitURL() yet.



In 2015, https://codereview.chromium.org/1270663002/, which added

validation for the Origin header, renamed SecurityState::CanRequestURL

to CanCommitURL, so the request_file_set_ check was now in

SecurityState::CanCommitURL(). That CL also split

CPSPI::CanRequestURL() into CPSPI::CanRequestURL() and

CPSPI::CanCommitURL(), both of which used the renamed

SecurityState::CanCommitURL(). The request path added a comment to

explain this: "If the process can commit the URL, it can request it."



In 2018,

https://chromium-review.googlesource.com/c/chromium/src/+/1108485

(tightening of CPSP grants) re-introduced

SecurityState::CanRequestURL(), which was now different from

SecurityState::CanCommitURL(). CPSPI::CanRequestURL() was now

checking SecurityState::CanRequestURL(), and CPSPI::CanCommitURL()

checked SecurityState::CanCommitURL(). The "If the process can commit

the URL, it can request it" comment was removed. However, the

request_file_set_ check stayed in SS::CanCommitURL().



This CL moves the request_file_set_ check from

SecurityState::CanCommitURL() to SecurityState::CanRequestURL() - back

to where it originally started from. The rationale is that dragging a

file should give the renderer process ability to request that file -

which is for example necessary if the renderer process decides to

navigate to that file, but not to commit it, since that breaks site

isolation guarantees. For example, dragging file:///foo.txt onto a

frame in a process locked to https://foo.com does *not* allow the

foo.com process to commit a file: navigation, but it may start a

navigation to that file which will swap processes and commit in

another process that's locked to file:. Given the history of this

code, this seems to have been the intent all along, so this CL simply

cleans up some incorrect code evolution that inadvertently happened.

The drag-and-drop functionality seems to be unaffected by this - all

DnD tests still pass, and manual verification was done to ensure that

dragging a file to be uploaded or navigated to still works.

Nonetheless, given that there have been tricky bugs in this area

(e.g., https://crbug.com/705295, a kill switch is also added for this,

so the old path will be kept around until we can validate that the new

one doesn't cause problems.



There was existing test coverage in two unit tests, where the

expectations have been updated accordingly. One of these tests,

PrepareDropDataForChildProcess_LocalFiles, was blocking Citadel checks

from being turned on due to relying on CamCommitURL() still being true

after simulating dragging in a file (which normally requires a

dedicated file to commit) to an unlocked/untracked process, which

should really not be the case.



See also the discussion on

https://chromium-review.googlesource.com/c/chromium/src/+/4764617 for

more context and motivation behind this change.

which are important to Chromium repackagers.

The _ideological_ reason is that the users can verify that the binaries we ship correspond to the source.

The _technical_ reason is that some buildsystems do automatic rebuilds on build-dependency change, and indeterministic builds result in the annoyance of frequent spurious updates pushed to end users.



You can read more at https://reproducible-builds.org/

entry.title: Don't copying error message in `Status` when the error message is std::string
entry.content:
A common scenario is `Status(..., base::StrCat({...}))`, in which a

temporary `std::string` object is created. Currently the constructor

would still copy the temporary string object because there's no way to

know if a `string_view` object points to a rvalue string or not. Let the

constructor accept `std::string` object instead.



This won't cause inefficiency if a char array or `std::string_view` is

passed in, because a `std::string` object must be constructed anyway.

While the current implementation lets it be done in the constructor

body, this CL makes it happen during the parameter list creation.

entry.content:
This is a reland of commit b512119e4a9fc312fda4cbe2e5945503a128c2f9



It was failing on the CI bot: "Libfuzzer Upload Chrome OS ASan"

I was able to reproduce the problem locally using the same compile

I also had to fix a patch introduced in between:

https://chromium-review.googlesource.com/c/chromium/src/+/5024295



---



To ensure there are no more CI bots failing, I scrapped the last 200

build on `chrome/builders/ci` and `chromium/builder/ci`

- https://paste.googleplex.com/6328539587018752

- https://paste.googleplex.com/6273557865168896



Among the ~0.9k builders, I did not find other new cause of failures.



Original change's description:

> Reland "PartitionAlloc: Rebase files against PA's include_dir."

>

> This is a reland of commit b0070c07a287677fbbb243c5f7a47fcd46be37b9

>

> This is the exact same patch. The fix was about correctly declaring

> `public_deps` in some fuzzer targets that aren't checked by the CQ.

> See fix: https://chromium-review.googlesource.com/c/chromium/src/+/5012923

> I also added additional tryjobs to improve the probability of

> success.

>

> Original change's description:

> > PartitionAlloc: Rebase files against PA's include_dir.

> >

> > Make partition_alloc to reference itself via its include_dirs.

> >

> > Goal is to expand MiraclePtr coverage toward major Chrome's

> > dependencies: pdfium, Dawn, Skia, Angle, etc...

> > This patches allows them to #include partition_alloc no matter

> > where it was fetched in as a dependency.

> >

> > Indeed, when built in standalone mode, those dependencies aren't

> > going to have "partition_alloc" under

> > "base/allocator/partition_allocator", but under their own

> > "third_party/partition_alloc".

entry.title: Add SessionId member to FormDataAndroid.
entry.content:
Android Autofill identifies form fields by their virtual ids. These

are generated from two components:

- A 16 bit session id that is unique to the Autofill session.

- The index of the field the user interacted with inside the form.



Currently these are generated inside AutofillRequest.java with a simple

logic: The session id is a static counter that counts up by one whenever

a new request is created.



In the future, we may wish for multiple requests to have the same id in

order to identify form's for which a prefill request has been sent with

forms for which an actual session was started. This means that we will

need some more control over session ids - preferably on the C++ side.



This CL is the first of two to migrate the logic of creating session ids

from Java to C++. It adds a SessionId member to FormDataAndroid and

a generation function for SessionIds to AutofillProviderAndroid.

A follow-up CL will use this SessionId on the Java side.
